> Would it solve the Swift/Xcode problem too if action entries can be named explicitly?

@rabbah It would help if we allow them to name the function whatever they want, and not require the function to be called `main`. In that way, having multiple actions in the same Xcode target wouldn't look to the compiler like they were trying to redefine a global function.

Perhaps another option is to have a backend/runtime object that allows the action developer to specify what they want to run as their action. Something that might look like:

``` swift
// tell OpenWhisk that my action's implementation consists 
// of the code inside the supplied closure
Whisk.declareAction { parameters in 
    // my action implementation goes here
}
```

Now that I've written that all out... this seems quite a bit nicer than the struct envelope that requires peeling away before running the action.

@rabbah I think we all understand what it is and also the reason why we named it that way.
But imho that does not help if a significant amount of users do not get it and that is what the user studies/labs show :(

@ioana-blue I agree, another name may help as well (many users seem to be confused by that term as they do not get the realtion to web feeds) but changing things others already got used too may be dangerous as well (not sure).

@sjfink Even though I understand what you are saying I doubt it will help (gut feeling); maybe explaining along samples may help? Maybe we should make a concrete sample part of the docu and explain the diff between all these concepts?
